name: 3-methoxy-4-nitrobenzoic acid
Reason: To predict the melting point of 3-methoxy-4-nitrobenzoic acid, we need to consider the effects of the individual functional groups present in relation to a base structure, which could be benzoic acid (with a melting point around 122°C). The methoxy (-OCH3) group typically has a moderate electron-donating effect and introduces steric hindrance, which can increase the melting point by around +20°C. The nitro (-NO2) group is an electron-withdrawing group that can significantly stabilize the molecular structure through resonance and intermolecular interactions like hydrogen bonding, increasing the melting point by approximately +50°C. Lastly, the presence of the carboxylic acid (-COOH) group will facilitate intermolecular hydrogen bonding and will have already been accounted for in the base structure of benzoic acid. However, its interaction with the nitro group (at para-position) could further stabilize the structure, potentially adding an additional +10°C due to increased rigidity and possible formation of intramolecular hydrogen bonds between the acid and the nitro groups. Considering these, the total estimated increase to the base melting point would be around +80°C.
